observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management organize a Market Committee composed of representatives from various Offices to perform the duties affecting market operations enumerated in the Market Code.  We also recommended that the LCE direct the 

(a) Acting City Engineer to prepare an updated or reconstruct the actual structure/ lay out plan of the main building and wet section of public market; and 

(b) Acting City Treasurer and the designated Market Administrator 

(i) to issue the necessary follow up/demand letters to the delinquent stall owners/ occupants for the settlement of their over-due obligations or initiate legal action, if warranted, to collect said arrearages; 


(ii) require the stall owners to observe faithful compliance of their duties and obligations as stated in the contract and penalize them in case of any breach or violation stipulated thereto, particularly on the prohibited sub-leasing of stalls; 

(iii) submit an updated master list of stall owners and reconcile the same with the actual occupants and numbers of market stalls appearing in the updated CEO’s structure layout plan; 

(iv) ensure that tenants are charged with prescribed rental fees inclusive of the escalation; 


(v) enforce revocation or cancellation of lease of stalls closed for thirty (30) consecutive days and conduct publication of offering to avoid idleness; and 

(vi) exert effort to locate the copies of contract of 248 stall owners, otherwise require them to execute updated and valid contracts.

We recommended that the LCE direct the 

(a) OIC-CDRRMO, in collaboration with LDRRMC, to (i) identify and incorporate, under a separate caption, in the LDRRMFIP the projects and activities to be charged out of the unexpended LDRRMF from previous years to facilitate monitoring and evaluation of the activities of the fund; 


(ii) properly and effectively identify LDRRMF related PPAs to be undertaken in order to ensure their full implementation and attainment of the expected outcomes; and 



(iii) update or revise the LDRRMFIP as necessary to effect the changes in the PPAs to be implemented; 

(b) Chairman, BAC and Head, BAC Secretariat to (i) ensure that the necessary procurement information or disclosures are timely posted in the PhilGEPS and conspicuous places; and 

(ii) submit the noted deficiencies in the procurement process and/or transmit the absent or lacking documents as discussed above; 

(c) OIC-CDRRMO and CGSO Head to submit the distribution list/list of recipients of the relief goods for the evaluation of Audit Team; and 

(d) Acting City Accountant to (i) strengthen her review function on the requisite documentation of procurements; and 


(ii) expedite the submission of still not transmitted DVs including the required documentary requirements.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the GAD Focal Point System through the GAD Focal Person 

(a) continue its efforts to improve gender mainstreaming to achieve full compliance with the provisions of relevant laws and regulations; 

(b) employ the HGDG in the attribution of costs of regular program/project to GAD; 

(c) ensure the complete implementation of activities indicated in the GPB to maximize the intervention in addressing gender-issues in the City; and 

(d) nominate the GFPS members for  seminars/trainings on gender analysis to familiarize themselves with the process and employment of HGDG in the attribution of costs of regular program/project to GAD.

(b) direct the CPD Officer to 
(i) stop the charging of expenses which are not directly associated with GAD; 

(ii) ensure the complete implementation of activities indicated in the GPB to maximize benefits inuring to the beneficiaries; 

(iii) inform the concerned DILG Office, in writing, of changes introduced in the DILG-endorsed GPB; and 

(iv) ensure that only agency’s major programs subjected to gender analysis using the HGDG tool are attributable to GAD budget.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) implement corrective measures; namely:
direct the Property Officer to 
(i) conduct physical count of all inventory accounts, prepare the corresponding RPCI, copy furnished the Audit Team; 



(ii) submit promptly the RSMIs of all inventories issued to the Accounting Unit for the immediately recording of issuances; and 



(iii) maintain SC for every item;

We reiterated our recommendations that the LCE:
a. instruct the CGS Officer to 
(i) update and maintain the required records, reports and issue the necessary PAR for issued PPE to end-users; 



(ii) complete the maintenance and updating of PC records of the said office; and 



(iii) prepare the IIRUP for unserviceable PPEs;

We reiterated the recommendation that the City Mayor :

a. Issue a written order to the members of the physical inventory committee, indicating therein the specific period for which the subject undertaking must be completed and the period of submission of the updated physical inventory report in accordance with Section 124 of the MNGAS. Sanctions for the continued failure of the committee to come up with the required reports should also be expressly provided in the said order to prevent the recurrence of similar lapses in the future;

b. Instruct the GSO and the Accountant to maintain Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards respectively, and reconcile their records periodically pursuant to Sections 119 and 120 of the NGAS Manual.

We reiterated the  recommendation that Local Chief Executive direct the Office of the City Treasurer and the Office of the Market Supervisor to 

(a) update the records of Market Stall Occupant Ledgers;

(b) explain the content of demand letters to store owners for the settlement of their delinquent accounts amounting to P2,744,581.00;

(c) cause the revocation or cancellation of the lease without the necessity of any judicial proceedings as stipulated in the contract of lease; and

(d) strictly enforce all the applicable provisions of the contract/agreement pertaining to the obligation of the stall occupants in order to prevent the recurrence of similar problem in the future.

